<ArticleLayout
  title="Nappy Change Station Checklist"
  description="A checklist for setting up a nappy changing area at home without buying more than the routine needs."
  category="Nursery & Kids"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  dateModified="2026-07-19"
  faqs={faqs}
  readingTime="5 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/Nursery-kids.webp"
  imageAlt="A tidy nursery room with timber furniture, soft lighting and practical baby storage"
>
  <p>
    A change area earns its place at 2 am, after a bath and when the clean clothes are nearly gone.
    It does not need matching nursery furniture. It needs a stable changing surface, supplies
    within adult reach and somewhere obvious for used nappies and wet clothes.
  </p>
  <p>
    That may be a dedicated change table, a mat used according to its instructions or a portable
    floor setup. Choose the arrangement that works where changes actually happen, then add storage
    only when the routine shows what is missing.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep the baby supported and the supplies close</h2>
  <p>
    The <a href="https://www.productsafety.gov.au/consumers/keep-baby-safe/bathe-and-change-baby-safely" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ACCC Product Safety guidance for bathing and changing</a>{" "}
    says to keep at least one hand supporting the baby, never leave the baby alone or in the care of
    another child, and have supplies ready within arm's reach.
  </p>
  <p>
    A strap or raised edge does not make it safe to step away. If something is missing, take the
    baby with you rather than leaving them on the changing surface.
  </p>

  <h2>Notice where changes happen</h2>
  <p>
    Some households use one fixed station. Others change the baby in the bedroom overnight and in
    a living area during the day. Track those locations for a few days before buying furniture.
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Is there enough light to see clearly?</li>
    <li>Can an adult reach nappies, wipes and a change of clothes without turning away?</li>
    <li>Does the surface remain stable when drawers or doors are opened?</li>
    <li>Can leaks and spills be cleaned without dismantling the setup?</li>
    <li>Where will used nappies, dirty clothes and washable covers go?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Test the room with drawers open and supplies in place. A table that blocks a wardrobe or leaves
    no room to stand beside it is not a useful addition.
  </p>

  <h2>Check the surface, height and stability</h2>
  <p>
    A change table, a mat used on suitable furniture and a floor setup create different trade-offs.
    Follow the instructions and limits for every table, mat or piece of furniture involved.
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Check that the setup does not rock, slide or interfere with drawers.</li>
    <li>Keep cords, blinds, heaters and unstable furniture away from the change area.</li>
    <li>Choose a surface or cover that can be cleaned after leaks and spills.</li>
    <li>Leave enough clear surface to change the baby without shifting bottles or baskets.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A portable mat on the floor avoids the fall risk of a raised surface, but it may be less
    comfortable for some adults. Choose the arrangement that can be used safely and consistently
    in the actual room.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep the daily kit small</h2>
  <p>
    The change area works best when the supplies used most often are easy to grab without searching
    through drawers.
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Nappies.</li>
    <li>Wipes.</li>
    <li>Barrier cream if used.</li>
    <li>Spare clothes.</li>
    <li>The household's chosen bin or bag system for dirty items.</li>
    <li>A small towel or cloth.</li>
    <li>A wipeable mat or washable cover.</li>
    <li>A nearby laundry basket or hamper.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Store bulk nappies, next-size clothes and spare wipes nearby but not necessarily on the
    changing surface. Keeping the immediate area clear makes the routine easier to repeat.
  </p>

  <h2>Give dirty items a short route out</h2>
  <p>
    Nappy changes create small mess often. The setup should make it obvious where dirty
    clothes, used wipes, empty packaging and washable covers go next.
  </p>
  <p>
    Put a laundry basket or washable bag close enough to use immediately and empty the nappy bin or
    bag on a routine the household can maintain. Keep creams, plastic bags and other small items in
    a contained place that remains out of the child's reach.
  </p>

  <h2>Small rooms favour portable supplies</h2>
  <p>
    Small bedrooms, shared nurseries and rentals may not have room for a full change table.
    In those cases, focus on portable and compact storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    A caddy can carry the daily supply between rooms while bulk nappies, next-size clothes and spare
    wipes stay in a wardrobe, laundry or nearby cupboard. One drawer or basket for spare clothes is
    often enough.
  </p>
  <p>
    For compact room ideas, the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/nursery-storage-small-rooms/">nursery storage guide</a> covers smaller
    rooms, rentals, wardrobes and supplies near the change area in more detail.
  </p>

  <h2>Night-time supplies need their own reset</h2>
  <p>
    Overnight changes need enough light to see clearly without turning the whole room into a
    storage zone. Keep a small supply of nappies, wipes and one change of clothes close to the
    night-time spot, then restock it during the day.
  </p>
  <p>
    Restock the night supply during the day. In a shared bedroom or living area, use a contained
    caddy and return creams, bags and loose supplies to a place the child cannot reach.
  </p>

  <h2>A dedicated change table can wait</h2>
  <p>
    A dedicated change table can be helpful, but it is not the only way to create a practical
    change station.
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>The nursery layout is still changing.</li>
    <li>The baby is mostly changed in another room.</li>
    <li>You already have a suitable dresser or surface.</li>
    <li>There is not enough room to move around extra furniture.</li>
    <li>A portable caddy would suit the household better.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If you do use a mat, dresser or furniture item for changing, follow the manufacturer's
    setup and use instructions.
  </p>

  <h2>The checklist before the first change</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Where most changes happen during the day and overnight.</li>
    <li>Whether nappies and wipes are easy for adults to reach.</li>
    <li>Whether spare clothes are close enough.</li>
    <li>Whether the changing surface is easy to wipe or cover.</li>
    <li>Whether dirty clothes and covers have a laundry spot.</li>
    <li>Whether bulk supplies can live somewhere else.</li>
    <li>Whether the room still has clear movement around furniture.</li>
    <li>Whether cords, heaters, unstable furniture and small items are out of reach.</li>
    <li>Whether the setup can be reset quickly.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Let the routine change the setup</h2>
  <p>
    Begin with nappies, wipes, one change of clothes and a clear route to cleaning and laundry.
    Move the caddy or restock point when the household routine changes. Furniture and organisers
    should follow that routine rather than decide it.
  </p>

